\begin_layout Title
Modelling responsiveness and willingness to negotiate using sentiment: textual
 analysis of the FARC-Colombia peace talks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Leslie Huang
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
New York University Department of Politics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
M.A.
 paper
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adviser: Arthur Spirling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This paper considers factors during the peace process that contribute to
 the success or failure of peace talks, and, of ultimately peace agreements.
 The FARC-Colombia talks from 2012-2016 sought to end an intractable half-centur
y-long conflict with a negotiated settlement.
 Using a new dataset of separate statements from the government and FARC
 (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia) and joint statements from
 the negotiators, I use sentiment analysis and hidden Markov models to estimate
 each actor's willingness to negotiate as a function of their textual sentiment.
 I find that estimates of FARC's and the government's willingness to negotiate
 can predict the sentiment of joint statements.
 I use a Markov process to estimate sentiment responsiveness, and, contrary
 to my predictions, I find that actors are unlikely to respond to each other
 with the same levels of sentiment.
 These results suggest that using sentiment analysis to measure the progress
 of peace talks is a promising new tool for research on why talks are successful
 or derailed by violence and, ultimately, what makes some peace agreements
 durable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do some peace negotiations succeed while others fall apart, and what
 accounts for the durability of peace after some conflicts but not others?
 Understanding the factors behind successful conflict termination is of
 great academic and real-world importance.
 Much of the existing analysis of peace processes and outcomes has tended
 to use game theoretical or case specific approaches, and empirical research
 has focused on violence during negotiations and implementation of agreements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, many scholars have modelled peace negotiations, for either
 interstate or intrastate wars, as a bargaining process or game 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "powell2002bargaining,fey2011uncertainty,pillar2014negotiating"

\end_inset

.
 Building upon these themes, a major strand in the theoretical literature
 explains peace process failure as a commitment problem driven by uncertainty.
 Beliefs about guarantees for implementing agreements determine whether
 combatants choose to resume fighting or commit to peace 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "walter2002committing"

\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, postconflict research has examined the effect of peacekeeping
 operations and other third-party guarantees intended to resolve the commitment
 problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fortna2004does,fortna2008does"

\end_inset

.
 Looking at transitions to peace more generally, scholars have used hand-coded
 texts of peace agreements to better understand whether provisions such
 as political representation for rebels in postconflict governments or territori
al autonomy predict peace survival 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hartzell2001stabilizing"

\end_inset

.
 Other empirical and theoretical work has examined postconflict institutions
 such as power-sharing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hartzell2003institutionalizing,mukherjee2006political"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regarding ongoing negotiations, researchers have posited theories to explain
 the variable effect of violent attacks on derailing talks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kydd-walter"

\end_inset

 and the relationship between government concessions and the level of terrorist
 activity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "demesquita-conciliation"

\end_inset

.
 Often these accounts are driven by an information asymmetry about whether
 actors are sincere.
 Other research has looked for peace process spoilers within the cacophony
 of factions in state and nonstate actors, with some scholars arguing that
 internal contestation and excluded or disgruntled parties can thwart peace
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stedman1997spoiler,pearlman2009spoiling"

\end_inset

.
 However, more recent findings suggest that including all factions is less
 important than originally thought 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nilsson2008partial"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In short, a broad body of empirical and theoretical literature has discussed
 many features of peace negotiations and their outcomes.
 However, to my knowledge there is no empirical research that estimates
 the status of peace talks over time---e.g whether they are deadlocked, near
 an agreement, or about to fall apart.
 Understanding the negotiations process is a key to explaining the dynamics
 of bargaining, the provisions that end up in agreements, and whether these
 settlements bring about peace.
 But no existing research analyzes texts issued from peace negotiations
 other than the final agreement itself, nor has sentiment analysis previously
 been used to study peace processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To fill this gap, this paper makes several original contributions.
 I collect a new dataset of texts from the Colombian government and FARC,
 in addition to joint statements issued by the peace negotiators, from an
 ongoing conflict/negotiation period (2012-2016).
 I use text analysis methods from psychology and natural language processing
 to measure the sentiment of these documents.
 Although it is difficult to draw causal conclusions from this kind of observati
onal data, these texts are a promising and heretofore unutilized source
 of information about the state of negotiations.
 I use the textual sentiment in hidden Markov models to estimate each actor's
 willingness to negotiate.
 To validate the model's results, I predict the sentiment and issuance of
 joint statements using the estimates of willingness.
 These findings offer potential explanations to questions such as why negotiatio
ns continue despite episodes of violence, and how the sentiment of each
 actor's statements affects the output from the peace negotiators---and
 perhaps ultimately, the peace treaty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I use sentiment analysis and Markov processes to model the responsiveness
 of sentiment---e.g.
 whether FARC is more likely to respond to a positive government statement
 with a positive statement of its own rather than a negative one, in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tit-for-tat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 strategy---and whether sentiment is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sticky.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Results about the persistence of sentiment may help explain the effect
 of shocks such as extremist attacks, while the findings about responsiveness
 can yield insights about the mechanics of the negotiations or about public
 statements as a form of signalling.
\end_layout

