\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimizing the number of states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This discussion has used a discrete state space with two possible states.
 In some cases substantive/theoretical grounds may define an appropriate
 number of latent states for a HMM; however, because the spectrum from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can reasonably be split into different numbers of states, I adopt an agnostic
 approach.
 The number of states in the best-fitting HMM can be identified by the Bayesian
 information criterion (BIC) and the Akaike information criterion (AIC)
 values.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In other applications of hidden Markov models, the number of states is not
 mathematically optimized because it and the labels attached to the states
 tend to determined by substantive criteria: e.g.
 in medical examples, values for various indicators of health that fall
 within certain ranges correspond to pre-set states, and in economic examples,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bull
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 markets are modelled with two states that clearly correspond with economic
 indicators.
 This paper uses a more agnostic approach.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To keep interpretation across the FARC and government models comparable,
 I specify the same number of latent states.
 Although the substantive interpretation of the model accommodates small
 numbers of latent states--for instance, two latent states would correspond
 to a dichotomy between 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 while three latent states might represent low, moderate, and high levels
 of willingness to negotiate, representing hardline, moderate and conciliatory
 regimes, respectively--as the number of states increases, the substantive
 interpretation of transition probabilities across these states becomes
 more challenging, and fitting the model becomes difficult because transitions
 between any two given states may be rare or nonexistent.
 I weigh these considerations against the models' log-likelihood, BIC, and
 AIC values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labelling the states
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because HMM estimation does not attach substantive labels to the states,
 such labelling must be done post-estimation.
 I explore two possible methods.
 First, I rank the unlabelled states in order of willingness to negotiate
 based on mean emotion.
 For example, the state with the highest positive emotion and lowest negative
 emotion would correspond to high willingness (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conciliatory
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), while the state with the lowest positive emotion and the highest negative
 emotion should be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hardline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 I also use a multi-choice decision matrix to optimize the ranking of states
 based on mean sentiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modelling sentiment responsiveness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second part of this paper uses a Markov process to model how sentiment
 responds to sentiment.
 I assume that the sequence of time-ordered statements represents a single
 Markov process, like a back-and-forth debate in which each text responds
 to the document that immediately preceded it.
 The irregularity of the data presents some challenges, as there are stretches
 in the time-ordered sequence of FARC and government texts where little
 alternation occurs.
 This is partly owing to the fact that the dataset includes roughly three
 times as many statements from the government as from FARC and that both
 actors sometimes release multiple statements on the same day.
 This means that a FARC document could respond to a previous FARC document.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To categorize overall sentiment of these texts as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 I constructed an indicator defined by LIWC-based research that found that
 in normal usage, positive emotion words occur twice as frequently as negative
 emotion words 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pennebaker-chung"

\end_inset

.
 The indicator takes on the value 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if the loessed proportion of positive words in a statement is at least
 twice the loessed proportion of negative words, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 I used this indicator to construct a categorical variable representing
 the four possible states: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC/low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FARC/high,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

government/low,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

government/high.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, the probabilities of transitioning from state to state are represente
